C. perfringens is what we believe made me sick. 3 days later, still not 100%. We left a message with the restaurant. No response. Safe to say, we won't be going back.

Was there celebrating my boyfriends birthday. He ordered a drink and immediately noticed that there were fruit flies in his drink. I think the server noticed as he was putting the glass down but didn't say anything. My boyfriend told the server about it and they replaced it. Typically, an average restaurant would give you a discount or take it off the tab; neither happened. The expectation at any restaurant is not to have fruit flies, let alone a Michelin star rated restaurant!! There was a fruit fly roaming around the entire time throughout dinner. Not worth the $355 (pre tip) tab for two. The food was average and small portions. You're better off going elsewhere for the half the price.

Found Gary Danko a few months back when I was scoping out possible options for our anniversary dinner. Called about 2 months in advance to make the reservation. Phone was answered promptly and I went back and fourth with the reservationists before I settled on a date and time. Ended up selecting a Sunday (our actual anniversary) at 5:30 PM. When we arrived at GD we decided to valet our car. The valet was fine, nothing special. We arrived a little earlier than our reservation time. Upon walking inside we were greeted by the host who said she could seat us immediately. We were seated at a table along the window. The table was set up so that my husband and I were sitting next to each other on the booth side. We were quickly greeted after we sat down and asked if we would like anything to drink. A few moments later they came by with a cocktail menu and the wine selections. They also explained how the menu worked and their portion sizing. My husband selected a half bottle of Patz and Hall Pinot Noir for us and also ordered a cocktail. We were brought an amuse voucher of crab and melon gazpacho upon being seated. For the meal, we both selected the 4 course option. I chose the Ahi Tuna, Horseradish crusted salmon, beef filet and the chocolate soufflé. My husband opted for the oysters and caviar, branzini, bison, and the beef filet. We were advised that since he did not order a dessert that we would be without a course at one point to even out the dinner, which was fine and to be expected. At the conclusion of our meal they brought out a complimentary chocolate mousse and some small dessert bites for our anniversary. The presentation was beautiful and the food was excellent. My husband and I are a young couple and we never once felt out of place. The staff are very welcoming and friendly. We were constantly being checked on by the staff. They were very attentive but in an unobtrusive kind of way, which I really appreciated. We really enjoyed the experience and ambiance at Gary Danko and will definitely return in the future. This is a great place to celebrate a special occasion.

Went here last sunday evening for an anniversary event dinner. It took more than a month ahead of time to book this dinner, especially for a weekend reservation. Came in here well dressed, the ambience and decor of the place was beautiful. we were seated within 10 min of arriving at our scheduled dinner. if you come too early before your schedule dinner, there is a small bar in which you can have some drinks and wait. but the bar can get very crowded, so we just decided to stand against the wall. we had the 4 course meal, of mine which consisted: seared scallops- delicously cooked and seasoned, i was expecting bigger scallops though. lobster tail- small delicate lobster tail cut into halves with yummy sauce.. duck breast was delcious. then for dessert , i had the chocolate praline with salted caramel ice cream which summons up my 4th meal. food was awesome, bursting with immense flavors and textures. service was superb, i cannot ask for more. i will definitely go here again. i left satisfied if not full.. i think it is worth the $$$$ you spend in here.

The restroom at Gary Danko's is phenomenal. That is one of the defining features of Gary Danko for me. That is a serious statement, as I really do invest a lot of interest in the restrooms of restaurants. One had a giant statue, the other had a fountain. They smelled lovely and had a very interesting ambiance. Very tranquil toilet usage. _________________________ Getting a seat was simple on a Friday night, we just walked in and asked for a seat, and were dressed casually: jeans and t-shirts. I understand I'm a terrible person for underdressing at such nice places, but I still appreciate places that don't treat you differently for dressing casually. There is a tasting menu, but different than most of the michelin stars I've been to in that there are fewer courses than tasting menus, but the portions are similar to portions for places with only a single main course. One also chooses what courses they want, which meant 4 'main' protein dishes for me. The experience was also quite different than the others I have been to. Instead of focusing on presentation and subtle flavors, Gary Danko displays very bold and strong flavors. Food: -Proteins in general: I thought they were all cooked perfectly. Very moist, tender, evenly heated, crispy where needed. -Lamb: Very nice lamb flavor. Sliced thin, made very tender. -Guinea Hen: I like guinea hen, and this was cooked so well. Not dry and without an overpowering sauce accompanying the meat. It let the taste of the guinea hen shine. -Pork Tenderloin: I've avoided this dish in the past, because I had it a couple times at restaurants, and they were as dry as an overcooked pork tenderloin. However, the tenderloin here was very juicy still, cooked to medium rare. Some tasty pork, with an nice soy-sauce based sauce. -Branzini: Moist, not too flaky meat with a crispy skin. -Lemon Soufflé Cake : Was actually disappointed with the dessert after having such amazing 'main' dishes. ____________________ Conclusion: I love the restroom. The bold flavors of the dishes are delicious and very filling. A different approach to tasting menus than I am used to. More similar to a 'Prix Fixe' (They are different in my mind). A better option for those who want large portions or don't care about presentation as much as flavor.

    C. perfringens is what we believe made me sick. 3 days later, still not 100%. We left a message with the restaurant. No response.

    12/15/2014Previous review

    We finally had a chance to experience Gary Danko after reading so much about it. Maybe it's all the hype or the exorbitant cost, but we left feeling like the experience was pretty good, but not great.

    The food is actually 4-stars. I enjoyed pretty much everything I had except for maybe the fried egg over grits. We both ordered the 5-course prix fix and I had mine with the wine pairings. The wine pairings were pretty excellent (as they should be for $85). I had three meat courses (pork, duck, beef) and they were all good, but nothing too special. The beef was probably the stand-out. My friend had the risotto (his favorite), scallops, bass and lobster. His favorite was the risotto.

    Service was great, but the tables were close together and we were sitting two tables down from the loudest, most obnoxious group of four in the history of fine dining (we started out sitting next to them but we asked to be moved). But we powered through so it wasn't that big a deal.

    Actually the highlight of our meal was the dessert which was wonderful in so many ways. I had the Louisiana butter cake and he had the lemon souffle cake. They were both very, very special. We're seriously considering coming here again and just doing a 3-course dessert tasting.

    In any case, I can't, in good faith, rate the restaurant any higher because shortly after leaving I became pretty sick. I had an awful lot of medium rare food (pork, duck, and beef) and if I had to guess, the duck was probably the culprit. As I write this, a day later, I'm still not feeling 100%.

    We would consider going back, but like I said, we would probably skip the entrees and go straight for the dessert.

    4/28/2014

    18 photos

    1 check-in

    The restroom at Gary Danko's is phenomenal.

    That is one of the defining features of Gary Danko for me.  That is a serious statement, as I really do invest a lot of interest in the restrooms of restaurants.

    One had a giant statue, the other had a fountain.  They smelled lovely and had a very interesting ambiance.  Very tranquil toilet usage.

    _________________________

    Getting a seat was simple on a Friday night, we just walked in and asked for a seat, and were dressed casually: jeans and t-shirts.  I understand I'm a terrible person for underdressing at such nice places, but I still appreciate places that don't treat you differently for dressing casually.

    There is a tasting menu, but different than most of the michelin stars I've been to in that there are fewer courses than tasting menus, but the portions are similar to portions for places with only a single main course.  One also chooses what courses they want, which meant 4 'main' protein dishes for me.

    The experience was also quite different than the others I have been to.  Instead of focusing on presentation and subtle flavors, Gary Danko displays very bold and strong flavors.

    Food:

    -Proteins in general: I thought they were all cooked perfectly.  Very moist, tender, evenly heated, crispy where needed.  

    -Lamb: Very nice lamb flavor.  Sliced thin, made very tender.

    -Guinea Hen: I like guinea hen, and this was cooked so well.  Not dry and without an overpowering sauce accompanying the meat.  It let the taste of the guinea hen shine.

    -Pork Tenderloin: I've avoided this dish in the past, because I had it a couple times at restaurants, and they were as dry as an overcooked pork tenderloin.  However, the tenderloin here was very juicy still, cooked to medium rare.  Some tasty pork, with an nice soy-sauce based sauce.

    -Branzini:  Moist, not too flaky meat with a crispy skin.

    -Lemon Soufflé Cake : Was actually disappointed with the dessert after having such amazing 'main' dishes.

    ____________________

    Conclusion:

    I love the restroom.

    The bold flavors of the dishes are delicious and very filling.

    A different approach to tasting menus than I am used to.  More similar to a 'Prix Fixe' (They are different in my mind).  A better option for those who want large portions or don't care about presentation as much as flavor.
